{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476261"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13710"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13710"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.44,0.39,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51436"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6329"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36720"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"3485"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51436"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents with a six-month history of recurrent infections. He has had four episodes of otitis media caused by \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, two episodes of pneumonia due to \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E, and one episode of sepsis from \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E in the past six months, requiring multiple courses of antibiotics. He was born at term and is up to date with immunisations. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He has no palpable lymph nodes or hepatosplenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to lead to a diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Lymphocyte subsets","Sweat chloride test","Nitroblue tetrazolium test","HIV serology"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s history of recurrent bacterial infections, especially respiratory tract infections and sepsis caused by encapsulated organisms (\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E), starting after six months of life is highly suggestive of X-linked agammaglobulinemia (XLA). XLA is caused by mutations in the Bruton tyrosine kinase (BTK) gene, leading to arrested B cell development. Patients have very low or absent B cells and all classes of immunoglobulins. \u003Cstrong\u003ELymphocyte subset\u003C/strong\u003E analysis would reveal absent or very low B cells, confirming the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may show signs of current or previous pneumonia but would not help determine the underlying cause of the recurrent infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esweat chloride test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose cystic fibrosis, which can also present with recurrent respiratory infections. However, the infections in cystic fibrosis are more commonly caused by \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas\u003C/em\u003E and other gram-negative bacteria, rather than the encapsulated bacteria seen in XLA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enitroblue tetrazolium test\u003C/strong\u003E screens for chronic granulomatous disease, a primary immunodeficiency affecting phagocytes. While this can also cause recurrent infections, it typically causes abscesses and infections with catalase-positive organisms like \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHIV serology\u003C/strong\u003E would be important to rule out as a cause of recurrent infections, but the history is more consistent with a primary immunodeficiency like XLA than acquired immunodeficiency from HIV.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["X-linked agammaglobulinemia (XLA) is characterised by very low or absent B cells and immunoglobulins.","Patients with XLA typically present between 3-18 months of age with recurrent bacterial infections, particularly those caused by encapsulated organisms."],"references":["Mazhar M, Waseem M. Agammaglobulinemia. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555941/","Cooper MA, Pommering TL, Kor\u00e1nyi K. Primary immunodeficiencies. Am Fam Physician. 2003 Nov 15;68(10):2001-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14655810/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36720"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36720"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-25T10:48:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-25T10:49:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6329"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51436"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positi